<hl>
<seg id=1> Japanese Prime Minister Hopes Miyazawa Remain in Office to Push Economy Reviving Plan </seg>
</hl>
<p>
<seg id=2> (Reuters, Ltd. Tokyo) - Japanese financial minister Kiichi Miyazawa received pressure asking him to remain in office yesterday. </seg>
<seg id=3> He expressed his intention of soon resignation last week. </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=4> Miyazawa's resignation and stay threw a shadow on coalition government of Prime Minister Keizo Obuchi's Liberal Democratic Party and Kozawa Ichiro's Liberal Party. </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=5> When senior officials' divergence on the issue of whether Liberal Party's cabinet seat is part of the agreement became apparent, an unstable situation emerged in coalition government. </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=6> Outside resources said that after Miyazawa's resignation, the Secretary-general Naida would work in his position. </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=7> Miyazawa indicated last Friday that he would resign before the end of this year but did not give exact date. </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=8> He said on a press conference: "I am not sure about the time." </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=9> It is anticipated that he will hold the position of financial minister until the end of a two-week special session in parliament. </seg>
<seg id=10> The parliament session will be closed on December 14. </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=11> Keizo Obuchi's deputy Cabinet Secretary Susuki told NHK TV station, he believed that Prime Minister would ask Miyazawa of 79 years old to stay in his position. </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=12> Susuki said:" I think that (Obuchi) in private wants him to stay and carry out his economy reviving plan." </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=13> Obuchi will talk to Miyazawa face to face. </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=14> He said:" Considering of his ability, it will be hard to find anybody to replace him. </seg>
<seg id=15> I myself hope that he would stay and strive for the prosperity of national economy." </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=16> Obuchi's public comments made on Miyazawa's resignation was he read some relevant reports and he would talk to financial minister. </seg>
</p>
